data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false"). Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with useful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check that a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *both* values, unlike `IsTrue`
- **`CollectionAssert`** — provides `AllItemsAreNotNull`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `Contains`, `IsSubsetOf`, etc.
- **Message parameters** — always add a message to `IsTrue`/`IsFalse` calls so failures are diagnosable
- **`Any()` over `Single()`** — use `Single()` only when you need the object; use `Any()` to just check existence

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);        // same order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);   // any order
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);
```

For richer fluent assertions, consider the **FluentAssertions** NuGet package:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
